<DOC><DOCNO> AP880412-0207 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-SurrogateMom     04-12 0189</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Surrogate Mom,0193</SECOND><HEAD>Tearful Father Drops Baby Off For Visit With Surrogate Mom</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD><DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A teary-eyed William Stern on Tuesdaygave his daughter to surrogate mother Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould fora day of court-ordered visitation.   Stern carried the 2-year-old girl into a Bergen County youthcenter, and a smiling Mrs. Whitehead-Gould emerged with the childand drove her to an unknown location.   The visit is one of the first since a judge on April 6 awardedMrs. Whitehead-Gould gradually expanded, unsupervised visitationwith the child, known as Baby M in court papers and legally namedMelissa Stern.   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, who sparked a landmark court case byrefusing to part with the baby she bore under a $10,000 contract,is allowed to spend one six-hour day a week with the child, withthe schedule expanded over the year to include overnights, holidaysand a three-week vacation next summer.   Stern and his wife, Elizabeth, have custody of Melissa.   A judge ordered attorneys not to comment on the specifics ofvisitation or describe the visits. Calls to attorneys in the caselate Tuesday were not answered.</TEXT></DOC>